<p>Hit it!</p>
<pre><code class="language-bash"><div class="line">php testing.php</div></code></pre>
<p>That's a helpful response: it has a <code>Location</code> header <em>and</em> shows you the
resource immediately. Because, why not?</p>
<h2 id="jsonresponse">JsonResponse <a class="headerlink" href="get-collection#jsonresponse" title="Permalink to this headline"><i class="fa fa-link" aria-hidden="true"></i></a></h2>
<p>We're about to move onto testing - which makes this all <em>so</em> much fun. But
first, we can shorten things. Each endpoint <code>json_encode</code>s the data <em>and</em>
sets the <code>Content-Type</code> header. Use a class called <code>JsonResponse</code> instead.
And instead of passing it the JSON string, just pass it the data array. The
other nice thing is that you don't need to set the <code>Content-Type</code> header,
it does that for you:</p>
<p><div class="code-block-wrapper" data-code-block-guid="cd1f608d3d">
    <div class="meta">
        <div class="actions">
            <span class="fa fa-clipboard js-activate-clipboard" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Copy Code" data-placement="top"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="info">
                        <span class="js-expand-all" data-range="1-98" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Show All Lines" data-placement="top">
                <i class="fa fa-expand js-icon-load-more"></i>
                <i class="fa fa-spinner fa-spin js-icon-loading"></i>
            </span>
            
            98 lines <span class="meta-divider"></span> <span title="src/AppBundle/Controller/Api/ProgrammerController.php">src/AppBundle/Controller/Api/ProgrammerController.php</span>
        </div>
    </div>
    <table class="hljs code-block-table">
        <tbody class="js-tr-container">
                <tr>
